Title: Linking forum posts -comparch-07-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.threadtitle: final - problem #7 part #7b block diagram question
Input.posts:
Students are being asked to draw a block diagram on the page itself. I do not have a scanner nor do I use drawing applications. Would it be fine to describe the block diagram in writing, using mnemonic for instance that could easily be mapped in some sort of behavioral model? Thanks in advance.
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
It is preferable to have a drawn diagram. \xA0Maybe you could take a picture of it and see if that works out? If not, there are online circuit schematic tools, such as Circuit Lab, that you could use. \xA0If a diagram is really not possible, I guess you could describe it in text or Verilog. \xA0Remember your peers are grading this though, so they must be able to understand your solution.

Title: Linking forum posts -comparch-07-T1.1
Description: The workers will be presented with posts from a forum thread where instructors of a course have replied to student posts. The worker is required to: identify the student post(s) that the instructor’s reply addresses. Instructor's reply post is highlighted
Keywords: tagging, categorization, discussion forum, forum threads, mooc
Input.posts:
Here is the student answer: MUL R5, R6, R7 ADD R8, R5, R6 MUL R10, R13, R8 SUB R20, R6, R4 MUL R17, R20, R15 SW R12, 0(R10) ADDIU R21, R5, 1 Basically, his solution is exactly the correct answer EXCEPT he moved the Store instruction arounds. I find this not such a bad idea, since it gives time to the MUL instruction to process and write its result back into R10 before actually using R10. That would allow the store not to stall since R10 is instantly accessible. However, if I follow the rules, I must take 2 points from its mark because , I quote : 'Please subtract 2 points from base score if solution reorders code that does not otherwise change correctness' What should I do? Did I misinterpret his solution? Thanks! :)
Upvotes:
0
Input.inst_post:
Instructor's Post
Please follow the grading rubrics as close as possible. In this case, it seems the student did exactly what the rubric specifies to subtract 2 points for. \xA0The point of this question is to break WAW and WAR dependencies. \xA0If you break the WAW dependency between the MUL R10, ... \xA0and the SUB R10, ... it really doesn't matter where the store goes, the processor can execute all instructions after the store despite the fact it is stalling.\xA0

Initially, when I took the exam, I thought program was in sequence and that 2 instructions would cause the interrupts above. After I read it again and corrected few student copies, I realized that it was for one single instruction taking 2 exceptions, so I suppose the same instruction once in decode sees invalid opcode and then in issue stage, it sees divide by zero. As per my initial thought and if two instructions caused these exceptions, then div-by-zero should then take precedence as it was the first occurrence.\xA0 However and even if two instructions are causing 1. undefined opcode (in D stage) then same instruction 2. div-by-zero in Issue stage, then I wonder how the opcode could be undefined if Divide-by-zero is also detected. Doesn't the latter implicitly indicate a DIV opcode? And how could it be invalid then? hey, I new few more points to go beyond 70.... hahaha. - j.c. pb8 in mid term exam: In a pipelined processor, a single instruction takes the following synchronous exceptions (interrupts): Divide-by-Zero fault and Invalid Opcode. Upvotes:

6 bits for offset (because we have 64B cach line. log2(64) = 6) 6 bit for index (because we have 64 sets). That should say you which set you have to check for cache hit/miss. 32 - 6 - 6 = 20 Having just one bit per set you can say which line was used last cause you have only 2 lines.
